The Named Data Networking Next-Phase project successfully finished its 3-year mission, from 2014 to 2017, of further developing the NDN future Internet architecture and moving it closer to reality. Building on lessons learned from the success of current TCP/IP-based Internet, NDN preserves the hourglass-shaped protocol architecture, extends the end-to-end principle to include both reliability and security control by end applications, and adheres to the principle in the presence of pervasive middleboxes and mobility. Recognizing the major shift in application communication model from "where" (i.e., hosts and addresses) to "what" (i.e., data and content), NDN allows applications to communicate directly using the name of the content they desire and leave to the network to figure out how and from where to retrieve it. To address the biggest weakness in the current Internet architecture, which is lack of security, NDN includes a fundamental security building block in the core architecture by requiring all content be cryptographically signed.

The NDN-NP project aimed to apply the project team?s increasingly deeper understanding of NDN?s opportunities and challenges to developing advanced applications running over NDN, to further the evolution of the architecture in the experimental, application-driven manner that proved successful in the earlier project. In particular, our research agenda was organized to translate the important results in architecture and security research into library code to help guide the development for new applications toward native NDN designs. This enabled us to simultaneously continue the fundamental research into the architectural challenges and explore opportunities opened up by NDN?s architectural innovation.

The 3-year NDN-NP effort led to the following major achievements:



the refinement of the NDN protocol suite based on our deepened understanding of the architecture;



an ever growing and increasingly mature NDN codebase, which includes basic NDN network functions, sup- porting libraries, security tools for conventional Linux and macOS, mobile Android, and resource-constrained IoT platforms including RIOT-OS, Electric Imp, Raspberry Pi and Arduino, as well as a set of NDN-native applications;



an NDN testbed that has been in operation since 2012, with 42 participating sites across four continents;



an NDN simulation package for experimentation with the NDN architecture (which has been cited by over 500 publications).

The above outcome can be found on the following NDN websites, which will be maintained by the NDN research team beyond the NDN-NP project:





the main NDN website, https://named-data.net/;



NDN tutorial website: a collection of NDN tutorial recordings and slides by the NDN project team, https://named-data.net/publications/tutorials/;



the NDN protocol specification, https://named-data.net/doc/NDN-packet-spec/current/;



the NDN codebase, https://named-data.net/codebase/platform/;



the NDN testbed, https://named-data.net/ndn-testbed/;



the popular NDN simulator, ndnSIM, https://ndnsim.net/;



the NDN emulator, Mini-NDN, http://minindn.memphis.edu/.

The NDN/NDN-NP project contributed to the global movement toward Information-Centric Networking in future Internet development. On the academic research front, both ACM and IEEE started ICN Workshop in 2011, and the two workshop series merged to form the annual ACM Information Centric Networking conference started in 2014. In addition, there are several ICN-focused series of workshops, including MobiHoc/INFOCOM NOM workshops (2012, 2014, 2016), GLOBECOM/ICC ICN-SRA (2015, 2016, 2018), ICME/INFOCOM MuSIC workshops (2015, 2016), IEEE MASS 2015 CCN Workshop. Additionally, MILCOM 2018 will host a special session on NDN. Using specific network environments and applications to drive the NDN-NP research has also generated experience that is now being translated into early-stage product prototypes through industry-university partnerships, such as the development of startup Operant Solar?s neighborhood solar platform, supported by the Department of Energy?s Sunshot program. The NDN-NP project also directly contributed to the formation of NSF-Intel joint program on "Information-Centric Networking in Wireless Edge Networks (ICN-WEN)" which was launched in summer 2017, and to the DARPA program on "Secure Handhelds on Assured Resilient networks at the tactical Edge (SHARE)" which was launched in fall 2017.








